@@eThe Rebuilt City: Kiess@@N

@@yKiess@@N rises where Evermeet once stood, built on its foundations along
@@eRoc Road@@N, the ancient trade artery linking the western frontier to
Midgaard in the east. Evermeet did not fall in a single night. Over
generations its outer wards were neglected, its bridges left to rot, its
supply houses burned without coordinated response. Eventually the last
defenders withdrew and Evermeet was abandoned to the wildlands.

The merchants, soldiers, and temple orders who returned did not come to
restore the old city. They came to replace it entirely. Where Evermeet
grew by accident and indulgence, Kiess was built by design: a walled
rectangle with predictable streets, centralized services, and controlled
gates. Locals describe the difference simply: @@d"Evermeet remembered, but
finally made defensible."@@N

@@eThree-Power Governance@@N divides authority among factions held in
deliberate tension:
@@WThe Compact Temples@@N maintain sanctuary law, civic rites, and the Prism's
memorial functions from the Temple of Concord.
@@yThe Trade Syndics@@N maintain market continuity and caravan contracts from
their administrative annex along Roc Road.
@@dWall Command@@N maintains gate discipline, patrol rotation, and the city's
four watchtowers from their northern headquarters.

No single faction dominates. The @@rExecutioner@@N stationed at the @@eCentral
Prism@@N binds all three to a common peace code.

The @@eCentral Prism@@N is a luminous civic keystone recovered from the ruins
of Evermeet's civic hall. It serves as both memorial and practical center:
public law, messaging, provisioning, and magical logistics are all
positioned within steps of it. The Prism is continuity made visible -- a
reminder that what was lost can be rebuilt, but only if the rebuilders
watch harder than their predecessors did.

The founding charter contains a striking clause: @@y"No sealed warrant
issued by a predecessor authority shall bind a Kiess citizen."@@N This was
no abstract principle. Foundation excavations uncovered an @@dobsidian disc@@N
bearing the Spirebound Conclave's triune seal -- Ember, Prism, Pale --
confirming that Evermeet had issued sealed warrants transferring condemned
debtors to the Conclave. Kiess wrote the prohibition into law specifically
to prevent its repetition.

White civic stone, blue-and-gold banners, and prismatic glasswork set
into canal bridges mark the city's deliberate aesthetic: bright enough
to signal renewal, ordered enough to signal discipline. Names of
Evermeet's lost districts are carved into waystones along the main
avenues.

To the north lies the @@gForest of Confusion@@N, where Wall Command maintains
rope-line corridors and bell-post networks through disorienting mist.
Beyond it, the @@gVerdant Depths@@N offer both wealth and persistent danger.
To the east, Roc Road runs to Midgaard. Kiess survives by organizing
risk rather than ignoring it.
